it.emarolab.amor.owlInterface

Class OWLReferencesInterface

  • java.lang.Object
    • it.emarolab.amor.owlInterface.OWLLibrary
      • it.emarolab.amor.owlInterface.OWLReferencesInterface
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    OWLReferences

    public abstract class OWLReferencesInterface
extends OWLLibrary
    Project: aMOR
    File: it.emarolab.amor.owlInterface.OWLReferencesInterface
    Licence: GNU GENERAL PUBLIC LICENSE. Version 3, 29 June 2007
    Author: Buoncompagni Luca (luca.buoncompagni@edu.unige.it)
    affiliation: DIBRIS, EMAROLab, University of Genoa.
    date: Feb 10, 2016

    This class implements the basic structure provided by the OWL api.
    It is not recommenced to instantiate directly this class or its extension, use OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer insted.

    See Also:
    OWLLibrary, OWLReferences, OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer

      • OWLReferencesInterface

        protected OWLReferencesInterface(java.lang.String referenceName,
                                 java.lang.String filePath,
                                 java.lang.String ontologyPath,
                                 java.lang.Boolean bufferingReasoner,
                                 java.lang.Integer command)
        Create a new references to an ontology using the standard reasoner.
        Parameters:
        referenceName - the unique identifier for this ontology reference. The reference is stored in OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer.allReferences.
        filePath - the ontology file path (or URL).
        ontologyPath - the ontology IRI path.
        bufferingReasoner - if true, the reasoner is triggered only when synchronizeReasoner() is called. Else, the reasoner is called after every change to the ontology.
        command - specify if the reference must be created or loaded (from file or web). Possible values forcommands are: OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer.COMMAND_CREATE, OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer.COMMAND_LOAD_FILE or OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer.COMMAND_LOAD_WEB.

                                 java.lang.String ontologyPath,

                                 java.lang.Boolean bufferingReasoner,
                                 java.lang.Integer command)
        Create a new references to an ontology using the standard reasoner.
        Parameters:
        referenceName - the unique identifier for this ontology reference. The reference is stored in OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer.allReferences.
        filePath - the ontology file path (or URL).
        ontologyPath - the ontology IRI path.
        reasonerFactory - the reasoner factory qualifier referring to the reasoner to use. Possible values are: [OWLLibrary.REASONER_QUALIFIER_PELLET, OWLLibrary.REASONER_QUALIFIER_HERMIT, OWLLibrary.REASONER_QUALIFIER_SNOROCKET or OWLLibrary.REASONER_QUALIFIER_FACT].
        bufferingReasoner - if true, the reasoner is triggered only when synchronizeReasoner() is called. Else, the reasoner is called after every change to the ontology.
        command - specify if the reference must be created or loaded (from file or web). Possible values forcommands are: OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer.COMMAND_CREATE, OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer.COMMAND_LOAD_FILE or OWLReferencesInterface.OWLReferencesContainer.COMMAND_LOAD_WEB.

      • applyOWLManipulatorChangesAddAxiom

        public void applyOWLManipulatorChangesAddAxiom(org.semanticweb.owlapi.model.OWLAxiom addAxiom)
        Applies an axiom to the ontology. First, it gets the necessary changes using OWLManipulator.applyChanges(List), then calls OWLManipulator.getAddAxiom(OWLAxiom) to apply them. Depending on OWLManipulator.isChangeBuffering() flag, those changes would be added (or not) to the internal manipulator buffer.
        Parameters:
        addAxiom - the axiom to be added and applied to the ontology.

      • applyOWLManipulatorChangesRemoveAxiom

        public void applyOWLManipulatorChangesRemoveAxiom(org.semanticweb.owlapi.model.OWLAxiom removeAxiom)

Depending on OWLManipulator.isChangeBuffering() flag, those changes would be added (or not) to the internal manipulator buffer.
        Parameters:
        removeAxiom - the axiom to be removed and applied to the ontology.

      • synchronizeReasoner

        public void synchronizeReasoner()
        If the Ontology is consistent, it will synchronise a buffering reasoner calling reasoner.flush(); if the reasoner buffering is set to false, then this method has no effects.
        If an inconsistency error occurs, it will print on console an explanation of the error. Such an explanation interface can be implemented with the ReasonerExplanator interface.
        Note that if the ontology is inconsistent then all the methods in this class may return null. WARNING: manipulation buffer is always flushed before synchronizing the reasoner by OWLManipulator.applyChanges(). You can synchronize the reasoner manually (non-buffering mode) by using checkConsistent()

      • synchronizeReasoner

        public void synchronizeReasoner(java.util.List<org.semanticweb.owlapi.model.OWLOntologyChange> changesBuffer)
        Applies some changes, then synchronize the reasoner. If the Ontology is consistent, it will synchronise a buffering reasoner calling reasoner.flush(); if the reasoner buffering is set to false, then this method has no effects.
        If an inconsistency error occurs, it will print on console an explanation of the error. Such an explanation interface can be implemented with the ReasonerExplanator interface.
        Note that if the ontology is inconsistent then all the methods in this class may return null. WARNING: manipulation buffer is always flushed before synchronizing the reasoner by OWLManipulator.applyChanges(). You can synchronize the reasoner manually (non-buffering mode) by using checkConsistent()
        Parameters:
        changesBuffer - the buffer of ontology changes to be applied before reasoning.

      • logInconsistency

        protected void logInconsistency()
        This method check if the reasonerExplanator is initialised. If yes, it calls ReasonerExplanator.notifyInconsistency(). Otherwise, it logs to console that no Reasoner Explanator implementation is initialized.

      • getOnlyElement

        public java.lang.Object getOnlyElement(java.util.Set<?> set)
        Utility method to get an object from a set which is supposed to have only one element. Returns null if( set.size() == 0). If the set is non-empty, returns the first value, which can change since the sets are non ordered. Example: you need to get the value of an object property but you know from the design of your ontology that an individual can be assigned only one value for that specific property. If more than one are assigned, a random one is returned.
        Parameters:
        set - a generic set of objects.
        Returns:
        an element of the set.
